\section{Discussion}\label{sec:discussion}

The issue of particle depletion when estimating the posterior distribution of parameter values using a particle filter has previously been noted \citep{chen25}.
A key innovation of iterated filtering algorithms is that adding parameter perturbations helps revive the particle representations from a depleted state by adding artificial noise to the parameter particles.
Given this mechanism, an alternative approach to solving the particle depletion issue would be to perturb all model parameters at each time-step.
This approach is supported by Theorem~\ref{theorem:pif}, and avoids the analytic challenges associated with adding the marginalization step.
However, perturbing all model parameters at each step generally performs worse on panel models than the PIF variation.
This is because the artificial noise introduced by parameter perturbations results in a loss of information.

This loss of information, particularly when perturbations occur at observation times providing little direct signal about the parameter, motivates the common practice of only perturbing model parameters at time steps where the data has direct relation with the parameters that are being perturbed.
For instance, it is common practice to only perturb parameters that are unique to the initialization density $f_{X_{u, 0}}(x_{u, 0};\, \theta)$ at the first available observations, as these observations provide nearly all of the relevant information.
This same principle serves as motivation for the PIF algorithm: perturbing unit-specific parameters while considering data from other units results in a significant loss of information.

The challenge of iterated filtering for PanelPOMP models can be described as a tradeoff between particle depletion and a loss of signal due to parameter perturbations.
The PIF algorithm is designed to address the latter issue, but the reduction in particle perturbations results in additional particle depletion when there are many units in the panel.
The MPIF algorithm is designed to address both of these challenges simultaneously by avoiding perturbations when the signal is weak, without resampling unit-specific parameters using weights calculated with data from other units.
The cost of this modification is a loss of covariance structure of the intermediate posterior distributions that is approximated by each iteration, invalidating the data cloning principle that has facilitated theoretic analysis for iterated filtering algorithms.
Theorem~\ref{theorem:GG} demonstrates that a marginalized version of data cloning still converges to the MLE for Gaussian likelihoods if the correlation structure of the likelihood is sufficiently bounded, and computational results suggest the convergence holds more generally (SI, Section~\ref{appendix:GGfail}).
This result is relevant to a much broader class of models, as those satisfying the LAN property behave locally like Gaussian models.
Consequently, convergence of the algorithm in a neighborhood of the MLE may inherit properties demonstrated in the Gaussian case.

Theorem~\ref{theorem:pif} provides some stronger guarantees for MPIF under additional constraints on the PanelPOMP model.
MPIF reduces to IF2 in models with only unit-specific parameters ($\Phi = \emptyset$), and is equivalent to PIF when only shared parameters ($\Psi_{1:U} = \emptyset$) are present. In both of these cases, the convergence results of Theorem~\ref{theorem:pif} apply.
Improved performance for PanelPOMP models given by MPIF does not replace good data analysis practices, such as performing multiple replicates of stochastic computations or carefully diagnosing algorithm performance.
We provide some recommendations for diagnostics in the supplement (Section~\ref{appendix:ci}).

